OK I try a little mock-up with a stateless deterministic MLP model. The value and policy network share the hidden layer.
```python
import tensorflow as tf
import numpy as np


class BasePolicy:
    def __init__(self, sess):
        self.sess = sess

    @property
    def stateless(self):
        return self.initial_state is None

    @property
    def initial_state(self):
        raise NotImplementedError()

    def make_state_placeholder(self, batch_size):
        assert not self.stateless
        return tf.placeholder(tf.float32, (batch_size,) + self.initial_state.shape)


class MyPolicy(BasePolicy):
    def __init__(self, sess, obs_size, hidden_size, action_size):
        super().__init__(self, sess)
        self.w_common = tf.Variable(np.random.rand(obs_size, hidden_size))
        self.b_common = tf.Variable(np.zeros(hidden_size))

        self.w_pi = tf.Variable(np.random.rand(hidden_size, action_size))
        self.b_pi = tf.Variable(np.zeros(action_size))

        self.w_vf = tf.Variable(np.random.rand(hidden_size, 1))
        self.b_vf = tf.Variable(np.zeros(1))

    @property
    def initial_state(self):
        return None

    def __call__(self, observations_ph, states_ph):
        hidden_act = tf.nn.relu(tf.matmul(observations_ph, self.w_common) + self.b_common)

        action = tf.nn.relu(tf.matmul(hidden_act, self.w_pi) + self.b_pi)
        vf = tf.nn.relu(tf.matmul(hidden_act, self.w_vf) + self.b_vf)

        step_fn = lambda observations, states: self.sess.run(action, dict(observations_ph=observations))
        return action, vf, step_fn
```
Note that this is just one way of many to handle the 'step' mechanics. I could also think of a generic `ModelStepper` that gets as arguments the observation and state placeholders as well as the `action` tensor. This model stepper is generic and works with any policy (right now all the `step` methods do look rather similar anyways, we have a lot of code duplication).

Also in practice we probably need to handle probabilistic policies, observation preprocessing etc. This can all be done in the Base policy.

With this setup we would pass an instance of `MyPolicy` to the RL algorithm instead of the `MyPolicy` class. Feel free to ask any specific questions if you need clarification. I try to answer them quickly this time.

